04943nam a22008055i 9780812292732DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)992454528  a97808122927327 a10.9783/97808122927322doi  a(DE-B1597)469617  a(OCoLC)945037567  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHN57b.A63 2016eb 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a307.762231 aAmsterdam, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRoaring Metropolis :bBusinessmen's Campaign for a Civic Welfare State /cDaniel Amsterdam. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b20 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Business, Politics, and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. At Cross Purposes -- t2. Detroit -- t3. Philadelphia -- t4. Atlanta -- t5. Businessmen’s Social Politics. Beyond the Civic Welfare State -- tEpilogue. The 1930s and After -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDebates about poverty and inequality in the United States frequently invoke the early twentieth century as a time when new social legislation helped moderate corporate power. But as historian Daniel Amsterdam shows, the relationship between business interests and the development of American government was hardly so simple.Roaring Metropolis reconstructs the ideas and activism of urban capitalists roughly a century ago. Far from antigovernment stalwarts, business leaders in cities across the country often advocated extensive government spending on an array of social programs. They championed public schooling, public health, the construction of libraries, museums, parks, and playgrounds, and decentralized cities filled with freestanding homes—a set of initiatives that they believed would foster political stability and economic growth during an era of explosive, often chaotic, urban expansion.The efforts of businessmen on this front had deep historical roots but bore the most fruit during the 1920s, an era often misconstrued as an antigovernment moment. As Daniel Amsterdam illustrates, public spending soared across urban America during the decade due in part to businessmen's political activism. With a focus on three different cities—Detroit, Philadelphia, and Atlanta—and a host of political groups—organized labor, machine politicians, African American and immigrant activists, middle-class women's groups, and the Ku Klux Klan—Roaring Metropolis traces businessmen's quest to build cities and nurture an urban citizenry friendly to capitalism and the will of urban capitalists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBusinessmenxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th centuryvCase studies. 0aSocial changezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th centuryvCase studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aBusiness.  aEconomics.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2016z9783110485189oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066591840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229273240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812292732423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812292732.jpg  a978-3-11-066591-8  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aE